FBQL Editor User Manual.
After you open the program, you will be welcomed by the initial interface:
To use the program, you can use the navigation bar
You can also use the tabs in the upper left corner of the program, when you hover
over them, you can select the desired item.
To create a new project, click this button .
After that, the window with the project creation will appear:
The left side shows all the blocks you can use:
All blocks are divided into 3 tabs: basic, composite and SPARQL. To move
between the tabs, click on the name of the block type.
After clicking on the tab "SPARQL", the corresponding window with blocks
opens.
To open existing projects, click this button:
After that, a window will open with the file selection:
Initially, the projects are saved in the folder ../Blocks/Projects/Project
After opening a project file in .json format, the project will open in the program:
In order to save the created project or overwrite the current one, you need to click
this button:
After you click, a window will open with the folder selection:
The format for saving the project is json.
To create blocks, you need to click on these buttons:
1 - Basic block, 2 - Composite block, 3 - SPARQL block.
The base block creation window:
To create a block, you must specify the name of the block:
Also, it is possible to insert additional information:
The main part is the field - "Script", where will be the description of the logic of
the block. The code must be written in JavaScript.
These buttons are needed to open and save the block:
SPARQL block creation window
The AREA block is the place where you can create designs from triplets.
AREA" blocks can be connected with each other, using the corresponding
SPARQL method connection. (For example - MINUS or UNION). Inside this
block there is a Filter field to create a FILTER construct in a SPARQL query.
Anything inside this field goes into the FILTER construct in the resulting query.
The "VALUE" block is needed to create a constant value in the triplet
The "VAR" block is needed to create a variable in the triplet
To move the desired block on the stage, you need to click on it, and then click
anywhere on the stage to make the block appear.
After setting the block, you need to write its property to create a triplet. To do this,
click in the middle of the block and write the property.
To get a triplet of blocks, you must connect them. You can do this by right-clicking
on the start block and moving the arrow to the end block. To give a property to an
arrow, left-click on it and enter its property in the text box.
Triplet Design:
In the resulting construction, the left block is the subject, the arrow is the predicate,
and the right block is the object.
To connect the two "AREAs", you must draw an arrow from the first area to the
second, and click on the arrow and name it with a specific keyword (MINUS,
UNION).
In the right panel there are 4 buttons and a text box for naming blocks when saving:
Button "Query" allows you to write a query yourself in text form, after you click it,
a text box will open for entering the query.
The "Create" button is used to create a SPARQL block.
The "Save" button is used to save the created block for later use.
The "Open" button allows you to open an already saved block.
The appearance of SPARQL block after its creation.
To work with the SPARQL server "Apache Jena Fuseki" there is a tab "Fuseki":
The Start/Stop Fuseki Server button starts and stops the server respectively. After
pressing the "Start Fuseki Server" button, the server at localhost:3030 will start. To
open it in the browser window, press the "Open Fuseki Server" button.
Apache Jena Fuseki Interface.
The Links field is necessary to insert a link to the data ontology.
The Prefixes field is used to add prefixes to the query. To add a prefix, click the
"Add row" button:
Then, in the line that appears, you must write the prefix in angle brackets:
Window for working with composite blocks:
On the left side of the window are all the available blocks that can be used to create
a new composite block.
By analogy with the SPARQL block, to put the block on the scene, you need to
left-click on the selected block, then left-click anywhere on the scene to display the
block.
The composite box has no restrictions on inputs or outputs. In order to make an
input or output at the composite unit, you must click on the "IO" tab:
These blocks are the blocks for the input and output of the composite block.
This is how these blocks look on stage.
Connecting the blocks with each other is similar to SPAQRL blocks.

"Open" - To open an already saved composite block.
Example of a created project:

button.
After execution, the arrows will show their output values:
The answer will be displayed in the progress window:
Also, the program has a built-in library - Graphviz. With its help you can visually
track the work of blocks and their relationships. After starting the project, the
program builds a scheme of interconnection of blocks.
An example of using the Graphviz library.
